Republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy because of the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people who die from the fall of lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this regard, these measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in the same vein, a majority of American governments enacted new laws from 2009, which made the registration or voting process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread since the November 2010 elections, which saw an increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011.
New electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, as well as proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of scrutiny and withdraw their right to vote for citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
For this reason, the republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photo ID.
It is important to bear in mind that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity card with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than $100.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states students, voters who most vote for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who often vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to submit such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Spanish vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators in 2011 supported certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wished to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators passed laws in five other states that favored the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, exactly the same was true.
They represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, representing 76 per cent of the electorate, represent only 46 per cent of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Department of Public Prosecutions intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, damage could be limited.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states passed the law requiring the submission of a photo identification document.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted for, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A report by the Brennan Center of 2011 shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to obtain the presidency.
It is too early to state with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
