The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, indeed, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or "less evil" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it's not entirely clear that it's Higgs.
We certainly know that there is a new particle and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at an important physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely safe.
Anyway, we assume that it's Higgs, because the chances of getting wrong don't seem very good, so we'll see what it's about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because it'll end up hurting itself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" consisting, roughly speaking, of some of its characteristics.
The physicists classify the particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's beginning.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not talk about here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature are propagated and with which the boson of Higgs would somehow be related.
These bosons, it might be underlined here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone at a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the bosons "bearers of force".
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it it takes to reach extremely high energies, a little as if it were an ice pond in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the CERN (the big Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring of circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never remain stuck to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not have it.
Now, what can you "contribute" to all these investigations, Mrs Plamondon asks.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and MS predictions.
For their part, many earnestly desire that they be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that spans certain holes in the model.
This, we have to say, still has huge shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences in the CERN so far.
Implications
The impact of such investigations on our day-to-day lives is difficult to predict, but we do not believe that we are wrong to say that it will have none.
For you to see: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would provoke.
They glimpsed scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the Bell labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory device".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light picker in 1969 in the course of his research into optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this catcher now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
