But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both book depositors, verifiers, coin issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the form of e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes consist of the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge thrown at the computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file cutting, that is, transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "streaking" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (zeroer at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the set chain of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit a fraud, one user would want to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
"The failure used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Weighty actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, such as the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounting and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the "giant discounts" were launched.
"They changed $30,000," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this coin, believes quite in the potential of this technology as well as in the transaction network.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, so they come out cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to start up in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They simply provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to impose itself, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB envisages revaluing the various risks, which are now considered high, if this currency succeeds.
