A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever as to the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years Egypt has been using an interim text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial confusion.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delusion" and continues "treasoning his word" and "pissing the law."
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a step to speed up the institutional and political crisis and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their draft to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversial one is wreaking havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or I vote for my text or maintain full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, a majority Islamist, voted yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be achieved, yesterday morning 11 persons, alternate members, were added in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As could be expected, the articles voted were unanimously adopted.
The commentators are also grateful for the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so many members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which is the object of all eyes, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "rules", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing but an advertising scam.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "the people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
The fears of liberals are further increased by the fact that the next rector of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of marital status.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of whom are trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity about article 220, as the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to rule above all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted on yesterday received many criticisms concerning the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will argue that there are few in comparison to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor shall the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by human rights associations.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they considered to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to be on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this noon.
The supporters of the Head of State protested on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for the holy land, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the majesty of Bible truths with modern comfort and pristine nature.
"AIF" identified the five most important reasons why Israel should be visited.
Reverence in the Holy Land
It is worth visiting the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that anyone who enters this "baptismal pile" will receive divine grace.
And Galilee, the place of Jesus' miracles: the conversion of water into wine at the wedding, walking on the waters, the calming of the storm and the crowded nets.
In this very place, Jesus appeared before his disciples after the resurrection.
But the greatest number of holy places are in Jerusalem.
The believers walk here the Viacrucis or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin "Vía Dolorosa").
It begins in the Fortress of Antonio, the Pretoria, where the trial was carried out, and continues through the streets of the Old City, goes to the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, the place of the crucifixion, the Stone of the Anointing and the place of burial of Jesus.
In this very place there is also the symbolic Christian Ombble of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem, built in the place where, according to a Christian legend, there was a tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for the Jews, the Wall of Lamentations; the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in the year 70 AD.
As is tradition, people of different religions leave notes here with their desires, which will then come true.
Perform a vertical journey
The ruins of the Masada Fortress were what remained of a secret refuge against the enemies, which Herod the Great had built in the year 25 BC for his family.
They are located in the mountain cliffs at a height of 450 m above sea level.
And getting there by their own means, can only those who dedicate themselves to climbing.
The others can reach this historic summit on the funicular.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort Hermón, where in the winter months there is a great influx of tourists.
To there, bus services are offered from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were supposedly inhabited on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
In this country there are about 300 museums.
On a single trip you won't be able to visit them all.
But it's worth visiting at least five of them, the most interesting.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
In it are preserved the ancient Manuscripts of the Dead Sea or Qumran Rolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological pieces.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
In his exhibition of paintings he has paintings by impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Cesarea it is worth going through the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tour guides or souvenir shops there.
The entrance is free, and categorically no donations are accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars shine.
And the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they lost their lives sound.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health
The three main tourist areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of them there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphin parks and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that in the Red Sea they are bathed even in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall from 21 degrees and the air is heated to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there they bathe all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is at the lowest point on the planet: at 417 m below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brine that easily sustain even those who do not know how to swim.
The surrounding landscapes are truly beautiful.
People come here to spend treatment courses with salt water, brine and healing clays and to strengthen their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put in order their broken nerves.
Touching the mysteries of antiquity
They are preserved in the ancient part of Tel Aviv, the Jaffa citadel, on the Mediterranean coast.
It passed through the famous maritime route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very place, he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists love to walk through the narrow streets that bear the names of the signs of the Zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls on the street of your "same" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find couples of newlyweds who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The theatre, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera shows.
Tourists remember
If you travel to Israel, don't worry if your English leaves much to be desired: in this country about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
The money for this trip is not recommended to carry it in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed to shekels (currently $1-3,8 shekels).
Urban transport consists mainly of buses, but in Jerusalem there is a fast tram and in Haifa there is the only metro line in the country, which consists of six stations and connects the Lower City with the Upper City.
Actually, it's from an underground funicular.
Travelling on any type of public transport costs 6 shekels and for this price you can travel by transhipment for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays.
From Friday night to Saturday sunset, markets and shops close and public transport interrupts their work.
But Sunday morning begins a new work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
There is a wide selection of dishes based on beef and lamb, soups and desserts prepared with coconut milk, the traditional Hebrew cream called hummus, a wide variety of sauces, Falafel, which are balls of ground chickpea, fruits and vegetables.
There are no street dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats who "walk to their liking" in an impressive way.
At night you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
The snorers love the crowded places and do not reject the sweets.
Car rental, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
Besides insurance, it goes out for $15 a day.
And the rent of a bicycle will come for 15 shekels a day.
Museum entrances cost an average of 30 shekels.
Israel in figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
The majority of those who came to visit the country and rest were citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, the United Kingdom and Ukraine.
The Promised Land, from January to October 2012, was visited by 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists, a figure that surpasses 51 per cent at the same rate in 2010, before the cancellation of the visa regime on 9 February 2011.
"The great and powerful" will take you to Moscow: immigrants save for language
As deputies and human rights defenders discuss the consequences of the mandatory examination law, timulators who trade in "false" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million immigrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
Since 1 December a law comes into force, according to which every working immigrant must carry out an examination to check his or her knowledge of the Russian language.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, examinations will be made mandatory for all immigrants.
Moreover, it will not be enough to give the examination of the language, but also of Russian history and of the fundamentals of the legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even in order to receive and renew the work permit.
The citizens of countries where Russian is the official language are exceptions.
Persons who obtained their education and diplomas prior to the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 will not be subject to this law.
Usefulness, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Russian Language Institute Pushkin, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the test in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, often managed to ask this question to the press: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the compulsory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First, the representatives of the Immigration Service respond, which will reduce the number of people suffering from "labour slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of working immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defence of their rights must be initiated before their departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
Problems are experienced by immigrants without a profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass the medical check-up.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, on the pretext of helping, put a "paid trip" to a creepy and narrow cove, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working from 12 to 14 hours a day.
We received countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they promise one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they do not pay the promised wages," confirms the Chief of the Labour Immigration Directorate of the Tajikistan Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be mad, little boss!
However, in the meantime, many citizens of Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they do not only know the language of the country to which they intend to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: there are few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks who can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, not to mention already dressing them, wearing them and buying them what they need for school.
When they reach adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first chance.
It's hard, if you don't know the language, they recognize it.
"One feels humiliated and inferior."
However, with regard to the language law, rights defenders pointed to an important point.
The exams will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most immigrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in the bureaucratic obstacles and difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only one thousand five hundred rubles.
The employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and cases of extortion appear.
"We are asked for a hundred or two hundred roubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be cheap, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was revealed that not only immigration registration documents can be false.
Several "false" language certificates have already been seized by officials of the Federal Immigration Service.
The falsified documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came to the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system from corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers that they would not have been able to pass the exam the first time they had been able to study the basic language course.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
