The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, what we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without specific data, but Germany remains a model in some respects, but it is not clear exactly what is best at.
Could it be better, for example, as regards the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make such comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we are modeling must face a large number of problems.
If it wasn't, it wouldn't be a benefit to them to cooperate with our office, would it?
With regard to our country's legislation, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been stated in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex-post controls, we need to have a certain delay.
For the time being, we see in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are changed, the conditions of some types of selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be beneficial, or rather a tangle for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations are "hardened" and impossible to comply with.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law not respected in the area of public awards meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense, then, to harden the law like this?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how does it come out of this?
We'll see where this initiated path leads.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc" system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the Prime Minister of the Government can prevent the Office from acting which has an obligation to carry out such controls and to demand obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say we're going to act like nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic to exclude the candidate with the best offer for failing to meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This, in my opinion, is what we lack.
