Šimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
It is said that in a little less than a month the end of the world will come, what do you think about it?
It's just one of so many other alarmist news that we like to hold onto.
The Tap Tap music group likes to make jokes about this and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to avoid it.
In addition, in December you organize a truly original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain this to our readers?
This is a state benefit that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential that has the end of the Mayan calendar enunciated for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The previous day, on December 20 at 9 p.m., we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time as the Mayan calendar ends on Kiribati Island, in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we were forging the project all together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of articles: boots, t-shirts, bags and original keys against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The Tap Tap group, along with other interpreters, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, entitled "End of the world, cancelled".
Currently it is very popular on YouTube, will you be able to hear at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and it'll be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
All the performers will sing it at the same time in the three concerts.
The hymns will be linked simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the leading role of Jesus in the video clip, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We work together even with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charity events and concerts...
We make every effort to participate in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and have fun working with us.
What will the money raised at concerts against the end of the world be used for?
To equipment for the educational center without barriers Studeo, which we have completed in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
Students of Jedličkův ustav school regularly receive visits from teachers with whom they perform fun and interesting activities.
Students do not have sufficient financial means to pay teachers and we make an effort to make it possible.
As part of the completion of the works in Jedličkův ústav, there will be an independent building to which we will move with this project.
In each concert several groups and interpreters act.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to develop a programme that is attractive to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Barra, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will act.
For more detailed information, please visit www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar "spectacular action" planned in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the festival Pražské jaro, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and myself, personally, taking advantage of the fact that we are in the United States, I would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have acted for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group made up of persons with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as hard as it can look at first sight.
There are five members in electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
So far, however, we've managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which I'm still surprised about.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything came out smoothly.
Thanks to the departures abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you found yourselves with so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the east, there is a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, there it is still not common for a person to travel alone through the center of the city in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as it is, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, there it is not.
Fortunately, a civil association had been set up, which was striving to thematicize the problems of persons with disabilities.
In what areas should we take an example of more advanced countries?
There are many aspects in which we go behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people to whom it directly affects.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with a serious disability to move on their own in public and can go to the service, to the museum, wherever...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate actively in social life, in this respect, with The Tap Tap Tap!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes for eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers to emerge, it will start to change everything for real.
So far, these are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The Tap Tap group is currently very popular, but if we look at it a few years ago, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered as an educator in Jedličkův ustav, where I had many young people around me who wanted to dedicate themselves to something.
And since I am a musician, I play, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator LÁJA Angelovič says, we got a little out of hand (laughs).
However, popularity did not come until the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that it helped us a lot to connect with famous singers and also to work actively to promote the group.
We come to the conclusion that the work that is not seen, is as if it does not exist.
With the help of the European Union, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential there was, that something else can be done.
The show world is full of things that look like each other.
It is logical, in its own way, that everything new is welcomed with caution and takes a long time to accept.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say that The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it's a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings who suffer and from whom we should have compassion.
There are people who are able to live a full life and develop, on the condition, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it is not just a breakthrough for them, but for society as a whole.
Did it help the fact that you're a demanding boss, as many people describe you?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many respects and demand some discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people come with a romantic vision and head in the clouds and when they find out they have to go two days to rehearse, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and in concerts, the initial euphoria quickly abandons them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and get something.
The Tap Tap Group currently has 20 members.
How many of them were already in early 1998?
Only one, there's Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come in and out, you can't help it.
