Argo Movie: If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group of Islamist students held the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomas as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation did not offer any positive prospects: to throw the Shah overboard could not afford it, since, if it did, it would jeopardize the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which later intensified even further with the failed attempt to release the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the negotiating intervention of the Algerian government.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
Iran's failure contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themes an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up at the Canadian embassy's residence.
CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for which it helped a covert story an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team examining the location in the country for the shooting of a superproduction of science fiction.
Gender combination
The plan drawn up by the "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
For the lie to seem truthful, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example can be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines moods. We find on the one hand well-documented sequences of Tehran. The credit sequence shows emblematic photographs of the epoch of events, which were similarly reflected in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And besides, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: men brought in to analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the halls of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Farewell Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where it was raised.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the local atmosphere was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran "swings" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the taking of the embassy is impressive because of its synoptic capacity which, at the same time, conveys the emotion of disconcerting and of the lack of forecast that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the impostor team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he manages quite well. Sometimes he adds something to reality: here it doesn't all come out so elegantly (the scene where the crisis in Tehran airport is haunted, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search behind his track turn into madness).
The weakness of Argo is the miscontrol that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserve more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic trace, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, value its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, that'll be hard.
As an evocation of a real history and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services can be, it is enough.
