The MVRDV architecture studio shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the library of Spijkenisse and the recently completed "mountain of books" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look, and finally there's something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby passing through the street.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a large company located near the library, points out: "In addition, the building is beautiful".
But I wonder why we need a library these days.
We all have Internet, tablets and e-books.
No one's going to be happy with those old-fashioned libraries, are they?
Spijkenisse, a city bedroom located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, bears the dubious honor of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how politicians decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, of the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, an entire master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings as well as cynics, took the theme with his usual serenity and attended the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked around and shrugged his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Citizens esteemed:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, the so-called 'Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises in the planned place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and townhouse buildings.
At the beginning of November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
In this way, the small town lacking history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather sense a central milk, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the covered brick floor and the elegant headlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up you can see the park benches, the dogs and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally book shelves are arranged along the façade and a huge dark room is opened in the center, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put the classic spatial configuration up and get the reading area out of the interior to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserve the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more a day shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, on a Frisian farm, we ran into the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years now, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of small millimetres of thickness has been used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was first pressed in such quantities until it reached plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous road of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment at the same time that maintain the appropriate atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is hard to believe this because of its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge pyramid of glass, even on sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located across the glass facade serve to give shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical information technology worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Similarly, traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She describes the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than an empty half-library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I believe that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved quite a success in that discipline queen that in the specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No matter how young and incultivated it may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a more prominent role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert in US-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather hairy diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany suggested that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status to the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, because of the special relationship between the country and Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I do not think that it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical with Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from establishing a flight ban zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is now reorienting its foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but are not used to doing so.
I think they are still testing their role, but they have already started the way towards a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries such as France or Great Britain.
What does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy which, when it comes to national interests, is prepared to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds strong motivation in economic policy, i.e. in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other major powers, and for this reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, he must be careful and not alienate himself from Arab public opinion or the Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it that much importance since it is not a totally unilateral relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as in the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not think there has been such a drastic break-up as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has managed to gain some respect for this.
After all, all this has done is to show that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different views on the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the US has been clearly in favour of a veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of U.S. domestic policy.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
