"Brand Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese Brands
Armani is a well-known brand worldwide and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the real eponyms do not file a claim.
And even then it's not clear that they're going to be right.
"Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their brands in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing's firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to record their brands.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the manufacturer of Puma sports goods.
Pattloch opens an archive where he keeps seats from Beijing's trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the brand Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also used the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are large warehouses of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of forgery.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
which refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
"It's harmful to the business, you have to fight it," says Pattloch.
"The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage the image suffers is enormous."
The financial losses and procedural costs of the sectors concerned are millionaires, especially in the case of luxury flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year China is, in size, the third market of luxury goods and the one that grows at the most pace.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a claim because it had been so long that the name that was the subject of the claim had already become a "market reality".
"If the plaintiff is in bad luck, he may even have to pay the plagiarism money because the process has damaged his brand in China," Pattloch says.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against the manufacturer of construction machinery Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by the German manufacturer of Putzmeister concrete pumps.
That's why today the Chinese can still use a very similar emblem to the Mercedes star.
Volvo's buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that largely reminded BMW; the case was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The Lacoste clothing manufacturer lost in China to imitations from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they have had difficulties due to the shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, "the situation of work emergency returned to normal".
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims processes has been reduced by 22 per cent.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75 per cent more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain outstanding.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As usual in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost one third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations around the world for the tenth consecutive year, according to the trademark office.
This also appears to be the case with the number of valid logos, a figure of 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been paid for rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as demonstrated by the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese copycat.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the imitator has managed to secure Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
"We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany the surnames are not protected," says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the appeal of the muniques.
In the next two instances Freudenberg has been right, but the opposite side continues to fight today.
You have to be very careful.
The case has now reached the door of the High Court of Justice, where it remains pending.
Wentzler hopes to be able to resolve the issue favourably and commends the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that "the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time."
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business file has had to review files up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposite side a "six-figure sum in euros" with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was not successful.
"This shows how much we care," Wentzler says.
The dangers that lurk in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe,
In particular, whether imitators secure rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group had long since abandoned this commercial scope, but had managed to prevent registration.
"We have to be very careful," Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend to German companies to be extremely prudent when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what needs to be done is to "register also in China all that can be protected", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the issue can be much more expensive than just a record.
In fact, if Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees by his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
