However, neither the Egyptians nor the entire world know very well what this 61-year-old engineer with a doctorate degree awarded by the University of Southern California really wants to save.
Do you intend to deprive the judiciary of its power?
In fact, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members at a night meeting of 15 hours, are truly troubling.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
What does "principles" mean, though?
This was and continues to be open to interpretation and it seems that the Islamists are going to take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the margin of legal manoeuvre that it carries, to impose a stricter interpretation of sharia.
This is at least what a new article suggests: in all matters relating to sharia it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power in all Sunni Islamism.
It does not have to be so, but this may mean that the clergy would control the legislation, something that - in fact - would result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's dictatorship these courts served to exert harsh repression on the opposition.
Following the dictator's fall, up to 11,000 civilians were detained in military prisons.
As stated in the draft, the State must protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values".
This is such an imprecise formulation in legal terms that with the help of this article state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
Clearly, this is nothing but censorship.
Indeed, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
On the other hand, another forbids offending or slandering the Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
It is not clear, however, what an offence is and how it is to be punished.
Just as dubious is the formulation that prohibits "offense to people"
Is it enough a president's cartoon or a joke about a lawyer?
Question of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Mursi for signature and that according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to the Egyptians for submission to referendum.
"The revolution is back"
The opposition has been closing ranks for weeks in front of the superiority of the Islamists.
Ten thousand people gathered in an unusual harmony on Friday afternoon at Tahrir Square in Cairo and swore to make the Act fail before it could enter into force.
"The revolution has returned and we will end up winning," says Hamdin Sabbahi, who is third on the list for the presidential elections.
The Nobel Peace Prize winner and former Director of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, declared that the draft constitution should be "in the bucket of history's garbage."
Through Twitter he accused Mursi's followers of wanting to lead a "state coup against democracy."
"When I call the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," says opponent Jasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been expiated," quoted in the Egyptian media as opposition politician Chaled Ali.
And several judges announced that they did not wish to supervise the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
"The Qur'an is our constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim community called for a counter-demonstration; in case not in Tahrir Square, but after a prayer on the other side of the Nile, at the University of Cairo.
Many women covered with a veil and supporters of the Salafists took part in it in the cry of: "The people demand the application of divine law".
They demanded that Mursi "clean up the country," while proclaiming: "The Koran is our constitution."
A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would have provoked a situation similar to that of a civil war.
It is clear that Mursi's supporters did not want to risk something like this.
The Muslim brothers stated that both those opposed to the draft constitution and its supporters would have expressed their views loud and clear.
Now would have been the time to let the people decide in the ballot box which direction the country should follow.
In this sense, it seems that the draft of the Islamists has guaranteed the majority.
"The expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious with this forced constitutional process that should have actually lasted until February and included all social forces.
This 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended Muslim brothers when they were held in prison or faced a trial during the Mubarak dictatorship.
Not because he shared his ideology, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this reason he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
"And now the expression `Human Rights' doesn't even appear in the new constitution," she laments in a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag".
The extension of Mursi's powers to the three branches of the State led to this lawyer's resignation.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of the democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, what the president has done is abolish it," Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could turn against him.
A protestor in Tahrir Square warns: "You are conceiving a monster that you cannot control."
The Norwegian Rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has any relation to its greed for an extremely smelly fish?
Take a series of excessively cured cheeses.
Put them in the middle of a mountain of wet, dirty football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You will then be able to smell the paralyzing aroma of the rakfisk, one of Norway's exquisite.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salt trout that is fermented in water for up to a year, depending on how smelly you prefer.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this treat of the most, so to speak, captivating.
"It eats raw and then drinks an aquavit glass of a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also what is known as the "Rakfisk General", who organizes the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is stored in small cubes and drinking from a drink important quantities of the drink.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," says Havard.
The drink can kill the smell.
I try some bits.
If you can avoid passing it near the nose, it is not bad; it is not very different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few kilometers by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty hit Norway and in which, before refrigeration took place, fish were stored during the fall immersed in water and salt in hermetic barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, obviously with inactive senses due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
At present, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13 per cent are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and even not much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered to be something important, an essential, albeit rather foul, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, it's all expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you the 10€ ($14) chiller each.
Norway doesn't usually appear on the international news agenda, and most Norwegians like it.
Here people are still reluctant to pronounce the name Anders Breivik, the extreme right-wing racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the event of July 22."
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own could commit such cruelty and murder.
After much of Norway's current wealth is the growth since the early 1970s of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as rakfisk trays pass and that, with her long blonde melena and her amazing blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, prudent people."
His English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like to brag."
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; everything, except a small percentage of the money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn't have during the years leading up to the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a loose carcass.
I'm in the snow lining up to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is definitely something different and quite juicy to taste.
But at night, that smelly fish comes back.
The hotel where I stay is one of many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that most tests the nasal pits.
A TV has connected live with a presenter who wears a birdie and who is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
Looks like the Eurovision contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls out of the chair, maybe beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a hard start · Global Voices
As Mexico's incoming President, Enrique Peña Nieto, prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant analyses the challenges facing the new president and the different expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad today.
In a city that, in the best circumstances, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads that lead to the city and that is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their place of work, but rather to prevent demonstrators from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and assume the management of the nation.
It faces a complicated task.
Mexico has been achieving good economic results during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is plunged into a war against drug trafficking that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence," Peña Nieto explained earlier this week to US President Barack Obama at the Oval Office.
"I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve that goal."
Before being coded with the president of the United States, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his home state, Mexico.
A very populated and rapidly growing state, which surrounds the capital; The opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory where he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, you are reminded with affection.
Its residents attribute to it the merit of the growth of tourism in the place and of the construction of infrastructures.
To get to the city you can drive on one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new roads, which is an enormous improvement compared to the cracked and bumpy roads that were rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques with their name at the entrance to a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We trust that he can make a real and lasting change," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, deputy of Mr Peña Nieto's party, the PRI.
"In particular, as far as security and economics are concerned, we look forward to the interesting and real change that our country needs so much."
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was unblocked by Vicente Fox in 2000.
MP Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, there are many expectations within the party regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the opinion that the opposition lacks the essence of the new president.
"He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He is a fantastic stateman and, above all, he is a person who knows how to listen."
However, on the other side of the state that is not the impression that many people have about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden under high highway sections is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called upon to assist in the fight against drug gangs operating in neighbourhoods and violence against women is particularly serious.
In a desert plot, located next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been abandoned in the last two years alone.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was the governor, a much higher rate than that of Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately famous for his violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Mr Peña Nieto's critics say, at best, that he did not know how to address the problem of femicide while in office.
The most critical accuses his administration of making a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the deteriorated neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to contain tears while showing me pictures of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the facts, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner murdered her.
"When I arrived at her house, it seemed like they had cleaned her body," recalls Mrs. Buendia.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared."
While her mother tells the story, a photograph of Mariana looks from the walls, next to a cross in which a single word is read: Justice.
However, that's exactly what the family says he's been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me like I'm an old gossip, a rioter, a whiner.
What they want is for one simply to accept what they say and to shut up."
"But that can't be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence," he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will be accompanied by a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has promised to give them priority during his term of office.
"I hope it's the same kind of president that it was when I was governor," says PRI Olvera's deputy in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, according to prosecutors
Prosecutors try to address Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse during his prison stay
The trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leak of confidential information in United States history, lost multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now claims to have suffered while in military detention.
During the interrogation of Manning at a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that the weekly visits of officers of the unit Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request that the case be dismissed since his imprisonment had been harsh and had already entailed sufficient punishment, came one day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks posted the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled out after Manning's visits during his arrest at the military prison in Quantico, where he was imprisoned in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the collators as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms do not show any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the visiting officers had spoken to him about those issues and had indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after talking about problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a board to review the suicide intentions she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was under.
The military said that they had placed him under that restrictive regime, which is below the level of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Navy base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was gonna die in that cage."
Manning stated that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, blanket, slippers, some clothes and glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even fall during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while sleeping.
He said if the cellists couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they'd wake him up so he could turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 regarding Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in his Thursday statement that, after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the jailers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said that he deduced from the order given to him by the jailer that he should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his slippers to self-injure but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, his slippers and his glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account the experiences he had spent while in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in case he was convicted on the war council, which was scheduled to begin early next year.
The defence stated that it plans to cause Manning to plead guilty to minor offences and to defend other charges considered too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detainee in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully triggering the publication of information on the Internet, leaking information from the national defense and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He claims that many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that the Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely come down the esplanade and reached the immigration processing area and was already completely confused.
Some posters indicated the way to two lines: one for "Mexicoans" and one for "Extrangers".
I stayed there for a few seconds without being sure where I was supposed to go.
As I grew up in Central California, my whole life I've been called Mexican.
It's ethnic tachygraphy, just as my Boston friends refer to themselves as "Irish" or my New York friends call themselves "Italians."
Later I decided on "Mexico-U.S.."
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthanding or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply an American.
I speak Spanish. I speak Spanish well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and put myself in the foreigner's queue.
I thought about that time this week when Mexico's elected president, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, there were: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also looking forward to talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why a Mexican is so likely to stay in Mexico at this time as to venture to go to the United States.
He wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style trade bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue to fight drug cartels in Mexico, although he gave no details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think for centuries, not in minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, the moment a US official says anything that carries the slightest criticism to Mexico, you start hearing complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma stand up for war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a challenge is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about grudge?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, somewhere in our family tree, there was one person, perhaps the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was closed the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit into a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, coming from a poor people, etc.
We are their descendants and loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican one.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look at us over the shoulder as if we were from an inferior category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came legally to the United States when I was a girl, reminds me that there is this spray between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she is considered part of the two countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel that they are not part of either of us.
We love listening to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of every country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico they see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to further complicate things, so I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised Mexican ambassadors, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and pressure the political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much grudge.
And with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be left alone with this idea, folks.
It's fair.
If some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their family members were treated a lot less time ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more Mexicans than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could well be an unlikely basis for peace
Could there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
In the midst of the futile and usual discussions over who first started, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the Israeli metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their former conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab spring has left it all torn apart whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been trapped in the regional uproar.
Perhaps this will make your struggle even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to believe that their lethal standstill situation could unravel.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism now seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November is maintained, this week's clashes have reinforced the hawks on both sides.
Hamas leaders, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced Israelis to withdraw, despite the fact that Gaza has received a good beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza under pressure in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to put an end to Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its relentless rivals of Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders might conclude that time plays in their favor.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a renaissance regional power that had previously been the closest Muslim ally to Israel, has embraced the cause of Hamas. Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf, has also done so.
The exultant Hamas members say that the Islamic half moon is surrounding Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hizbullah militia party dominates, passing through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist trend could overthrow Bashar Assad, until they reach Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern flank of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, unlike the most populous and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the lay despot who ruled in Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brothers are cousins of Hamas and their leaders depend more on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
In the meantime, Israel's hard wing will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, they have put Hamas in place.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep quieter... for a while.
With regard to diplomacy, the United States was stronger than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for initiating the last wave of violence.
Above all, Israel has prospered, especially under the rule of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have ended the lives of some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, partly because of the barrier that corrodes the West Bank, the main piece of an aspiring territory to become a state of Palestine, and it protects Jewish settlements that continue to increase despite the fact that, according to international law, they are illegal.
Mr Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even tougher line led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the elections on 22 January, is in a good position.
Why pamper those Palestinian crooks by giving them a state of their own?
If they actually ruled in the West Bank, would they not fire rockets as their fellow countrymen in Gaza have done?
It's better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their heads.
The hard wing may be imposed, although the Arab spring could alter their calculations.
Although Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have too much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defence budget is greater than that of its four Arab neighbours together.
Starting a war with the superpower of the area will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to get the ceasefire is a good omen and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a dustbin that will one day explode in the territories occupied by Israel, in the same way that this week a bus exploded in Tel Aviv.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demography worsens the situation as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to reject Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution continues to be one that preaches sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and Israel's transfer of territory for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more impetus to the outsiders who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to curb the entry of weapons into Gaza, together with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented situation to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land exchanges and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs outside the issue should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual status category in the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Again in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to devote his attention to him.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
