I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting duty-free shops.
But more and more academics and child development experts praise the goodness of boredom.
According to them, it's okay for us and our children to get bored from time to time.
Aborting forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom in a good spirit?
Yeah.
And no.
But we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" ("The boredom, an animated story") published in 2011 by Yale University Press, says, this is not the case.
"In fact, the story of boredom is very extensive," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin graffiti on boredom dating back to the 1st century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a variety of ways," says John D. Eastwood, Professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and putting the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "desire, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you".
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly."
The boredom may sound terribly similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that although they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be so.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading the article in a magazine.
Some groups listened in the adjoining room to a full-volume television program that did not have any relationship, others listened to it with low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, the alteration of attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, Professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting defective parts in a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not get bored."
"In fact, we now know that moving or sneezing, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it, as they make that person more physically alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to remain still," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring film.
But some people tend to get bored more than others.
To help measure this, some researchers developed in the 1980s a "trend to boredom" scale.
The scale includes issues such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things I'm interested in that I don't have time to do everything."
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using such scales, researchers have discovered that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external stimulation and more varied.
But, in general, teenagers are a kind of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, carried out an experiment in which 400 adolescents and their parents were contacted seven to eight times a day through a search.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers said he was bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said he was bored when he wasn't in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know if the current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that "adulthood is a time when boredom reaches its highest levels," largely because both children and adolescents are not given great control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: Is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into substance consumption as a method of combating it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
"A boredom is the way the brain has to tell you that you should be doing something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's most appropriate.
If you're bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
"So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to dose himself," says Professor Fenske.
And "that ability to dose applies to other situations," he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of him either.
Our aim should be, rather, to feel comfortable separated from the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our view, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate it to something worth it," he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated," he says, "it is difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops."
