Once up, they open up among tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tiringly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has operated the volcano since 1960 and, never before, to its workers, to which it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) per kilo of sulphur.
It is then sold for Rs 10,000 (83 cents of euro) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As usual it is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually carries out three daily doors.
It takes three hours each and ends up grinding, but they allow you to gather 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would gain in the field.
"The newspaper of the miners is very high here, where the collection of coffee is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", the carrier, who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali, explains.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the slice was not as hard, but Anto has returned to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a weighty reason that, in Indonesia, is as strong as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes get irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing his skin on the Kawah Ijen, whose sulphur has already begun to pass him a bill despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, he coughs constantly and his eyes get irritated by the toxic gases that fire the volcano.
It's the price you have to pay to get your dream.
"I will work two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Chastised by life, this nice and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden cabin with other carriers, it rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not stop manning at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends to the crater lighting himself with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its small profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs or provide any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and to so much weight.
In fact, they don't even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera that, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is for the beasts and not for the people," says Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been in Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working "all he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and darkens the eyes when the wind changes suddenly and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases... beyond, of course, their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pains and sores on the shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions start 15 tons of sulfur to the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a path of goats between the weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik proclaims opening his mouth well, where he lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30 years old, also works carrying sulphur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: the one that makes the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
