Journalists ' access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the soundless video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, restricted audio".
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media asking for more data.
Subsequently, the Peruvian Presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this is about Humala's pronouncement, and not about the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently demanded by the press, also the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was not disseminated.
On the official ASPA website it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international events, the Peruvian authorities worked to ensure that transmission systems were in place for all journalists, but they limited the collection of information to the maximum extent possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague that resolves a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
