This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he had an irresistible hook: The end of the "long countdown" of the Maya Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have clinged as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what he expected in the next couple of months: Hurricane Sandy, a cataclysmic fiscal precipice that some have called "deudarmagedon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the late Christian theorists believe that the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé said this week to students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
